From the table, we find that the absolute maximum of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>f</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> over the interval [1, 3] is <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> and it occurs at <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>.</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>.</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> The absolute minimum of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>f</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> over the interval [1, 3] is <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mn>&#8722;2</mn><mo>,</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mn>&#8722;2</mn><mo>,</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> and it occurs at <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> as shown in the following graph.<span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
