We conclude that the absolute maximum of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>f</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> over the interval [0, 2] is zero, and it occurs at <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> The absolute minimum is &#8722;2, and it occurs at <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> as shown in the following graph.<span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
