<p id="fs-id1165042278285">Answers will vary</p>
</div>
</div>
<div data-type="exercise" id="fs-id1165042278290">
<div data-type="problem" id="fs-id1165042278292">
<p id="fs-id1165042278294">Can you have a finite absolute maximum for <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> over <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mtext>&#8722;</mtext><mi>&#8734;</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>&#8734;</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>?</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mtext>&#8722;</mtext><mi>&#8734;</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>&#8734;</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>?</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> Explain why or why not using graphical arguments.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div data-type="exercise" id="fs-id1165042278366">
<div data-type="problem" id="fs-id1165042278368">
<p id="fs-id1165042278370">Can you have a finite absolute maximum for <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>d</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>d</mi></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> over <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mtext>&#8722;</mtext><mi>&#8734;</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>&#8734;</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mtext>&#8722;</mtext><mi>&#8734;</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>&#8734;</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> assuming <em data-effect="italics">a</em> is non-zero? Explain why or why not using graphical arguments.</p>
</div>
<div data-type="solution" id="fs-id1165042278434">
<p id="fs-id1165042278437">No; answers will vary</p>
</div>
</div>
<div data-type="exercise" id="fs-id1165042278442">
<div data-type="problem" id="fs-id1165042278444">
<p id="fs-id1165042278446">Let <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>m</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> be the number of local minima and <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>M</mi></annotation-xml></semantics></math> be the number of local maxima. Can you create a function where <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>?</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>?</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> Draw a graph to support your explanation.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div data-type="exercise" id="fs-id1165042065906">
<div data-type="problem" id="fs-id1165042065908">
<p id="fs-id1165042065910">Is it possible to have more than one absolute maximum? Use a graphical argument to prove your hypothesis.</p>
</div>
<div data-type="solution" id="fs-id1165042065915">
<p id="fs-id1165042065918">Since the absolute maximum is the function (output) value rather than the <em data-effect="italics">x</em> value, the answer is no; answers will vary</p>
</div>
</div>
<div data-type="exercise" id="fs-id1165042065928">
<div data-type="problem" id="fs-id1165042065930">
<p id="fs-id1165042065932">Is it possible to have no absolute minimum or maximum for a function? If so, construct such a function. If not, explain why this is not possible.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div data-type="exercise" id="fs-id1165042065945">
<div data-type="problem" id="fs-id1165042065948">
<p id="fs-id1165042065950"><strong data-effect="bold">[T]</strong> Graph the function <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>e</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup><mo>.</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>e</mi><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></msup><mo>.</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> For which values of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo></annotation-xml></semantics></math> on any infinite domain, will you have an absolute minimum and absolute maximum?</p>
</div>
<div data-type="solution" id="fs-id1165042065983">
<p id="fs-id1165042065985">When <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math></p>
</div>
</div>
<p id="fs-id1165042065999">For the following exercises, determine where the local and absolute maxima and minima occur on the graph given. Assume domains are closed intervals unless otherwise specified.</p>
<div data-type="exercise" id="fs-id1165042066003">
<div data-type="problem" id="fs-id1165042066006">
<span data-type="media" id="fs-id1165042066010" data-alt="The function graphed starts at (&#8722;4, 60), decreases rapidly to (&#8722;3, &#8722;40), increases to (&#8722;1, 10) before decreasing slowly to (2, 0), at which point it increases rapidly to (3, 30).">
